{{Greek myth (personified)}}
:

In [[Greek mythology]], '''Aoede''' {{IPAc-en|eɪ|ˈ|iː|d|iː}} ({{lang-grc|Ἀοιδή}}, ''Aoidē'') was one of the three original ([[Boeotia|Boeotian]]) [[Muse|muses]], which later expanded to five, before the Nine Olympian Muses were named.  Her sisters were [[Melete]] and [[Mneme]]. She was the muse of voice and song. According to Greek mythology, she is the daughter of [[Zeus]], the King of the Gods, and [[Mnemosyne]], the goddess of memory. 

She lends her name to the [[natural satellite|moon]] [[Jupiter XLI]], also called Aoede, which orbits the planet [[Jupiter (astronomy)|Jupiter]].

