{{Infobox song | Name = Jewish Princess | Artist = [[Frank Zappa]] | Album = [[Sheik Yerbouti]] | Released = {{Start date|1979|03|3}} | Format = [[LP record]] | Recorded = October 30, 1977 | Venue = [[Palladium (New York City)|The Palladium]], New York City | Genre = [[Comedy rock]], [[Pop music|pop]] | Length = {{Duration|m=3|s=16}} | Writer = Frank Zappa | Label = [[Zappa Records|Zappa]] | Producer = Frank Zappa | prev = "[[Dancin' Fool]]" | prev_no = 15 | track_no = 16 | next = "Wild Love" | next_no = 17 | Misc = }} "'''Jewish Princess'''" is a song by [[Frank Zappa]] released on his album ''[[Sheik Yerbouti]]'' in 1979. The song is a humorous look at the [[Jewish-American princess stereotype]] which attracted attention from the [[Anti-Defamation League]], to which Zappa denied an apology, arguing: "Unlike the unicorn, such creatures do exist — and deserve to be 'commemorated' with their own special opus". In an interview with ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]'' magazine he was almost offended saying, "…as if to say there is no such thing as a Jewish Princess. Like I invented this?"<ref name="LLC1991">{{cite book|author=SPIN Media LLC|title=SPIN|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wbkGT02oWs4C&pg=PA91|date=July 1991|publisher=SPIN Media LLC|pages=91–|issn=0886-3032|accessdate=2015-08-14}}</ref>
Biographer Barry Miles claimed in his book, ''Frank Zappa'' (Atlantic Books of London, 2005), that the ADL asked the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to ban the record from being played on the air – a symbolic effort given that the song was not being played anyway. This led to the rumor that a legal action had been filed against Zappa, a charge he vehemently denied in a CNN interview on "The Freeman Report" show of October 26, 1981.<ref name="killuglyradio">{{cite web|url=http://www.killuglyradio.com/2010/01/01/zappa-on-freeman-report-cnn-october-26th-1981/|title=Zappa on &#8220;Freeman Report&#8221; CNN &#8211; October 26th, 1981 &#124; Kill Ugly Radio|publisher=killuglyradio.com|accessdate=2015-08-14}}</ref> Zappa claimed that offensive songs such as this are why ''Sheik Yerbouti'' became one of his best selling albums of all time. Although it had little play in concert, it was included on Zappa's theme collection ''[[Have I Offended Someone?]]''<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=Real Frank Zappa Book|author1=Zappa, F.|author2=Occhiogrosso, P.|date=1990|publisher=Simon & Schuster|isbn=9780671705725|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=FB0O_HCpBy0C&pg=RA1-PA226|pages=1–226|accessdate=2015-08-14}}</ref><ref name="allmusic">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/jewish-princess-mt0002453060|title=Jewish Princess - Frank Zappa &#124; Listen, Appearances, Song Review &#124; AllMusic|publisher=allmusic.com|accessdate=2015-08-14}}</ref>
