{{Discrimination sidebar}}
'''Trailer trash''' is a derogatory [[North American English]] term for [[poverty|poor people]] living in a [[travel trailer|trailer]] or a [[mobile home]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Spears|first1=Richard A.|title=McGraw-Hill's Dictionary of American Slang and Colloquial Expressions:|date=1 Oct 2005|publisher=McGraw-Hill|isbn=0071461078|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/McGraw-Hills-Dictionary-American-Colloquial-Expressions/dp/0071461078|accessdate=24 February 2015|quote=the poorest of people who live in run-down house trailers in bad neighborhoods. (Used with singular or plural force. Rude and derogatory.) : She's just trailer trash. Probably doesn't even own shoes.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Collins English Dictionary - Complete & Unabridged 10th Edition|publisher=HarperCollins Publishers|accessdate=11 January 2013|quote=poor people living in trailer parks in the US}}</ref> It is particularly used to denigrate [[white people]] living in such circumstances<ref>{{cite web|title=Dictionary.com's 21st Century Lexicon|publisher=Dictionary.com, LLC.|accessdate=11 January 2013|quote=a poor, lower-class white person, esp. one living in a mobile home with trash in the vicinity}}</ref> and can be considered to fall within the category of racial/[[ethnic slur]]s.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Henderson|first=Anita|title=What's in a Slur?|journal=American Speech|date=Spring 2003|volume=78|issue=1|pages=52–74 |url=http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/as/summary/v078/78.1henderson.html|accessdate=11 January 2013|doi=10.1215/00031283-78-1-52}}</ref>
==History== In the mid-20th century, poor whites who could not afford to buy suburban-style [[tract housing]] began to purchase mobile homes, which were not only cheaper, but which could be easily relocated if work in one location ran out. These &ndash; sometimes by choice and sometimes through local [[zoning laws]] &ndash; gathered in trailer camps, and the people who lived in them became known as "trailer trash". Despite many of them having jobs, albeit sometimes itinerant ones, the character flaws that had been perceived in [[white trash|poor white trash]] in the past were transferred to trailer trash, and trailer camps or parks were seen as being inhabited by retired persons, migrant workers, and, generally, the poor. By 1968, a survey found that only 13% of those who owned and lived in mobile homes had [[White-collar worker|white collar]] jobs.<ref name=isen240>[[Nancy Isenberg|Isenberg, Nancy]] (2016) ''White Trash: The 400-Year Untold History of Class in America'' New York: Penguin. pp.240-47 {{isbn|978-0-14-312967-7}}</ref>
Trailers got their start in the 1930s, and their use proliferated during the housing shortage of [[World War II]], when the Federal government used as many as 30,000 of them to house defense workers, soldiers and sailors throughout the country, but especially around areas with a large military or defense presence, such as [[Mobile, Alabama]] and [[Pascagoula, Mississippi]]. In her book ''Journey Through Chaos'', reporter [[Agnes E. Meyer|Agnes Meyer]] of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' travelled throughout the country, reporting on the condition of the "neglected rural areas", and described the people who lived in the trailers, tents and shacks in such areas as malnourished, unable to read or write, and generally ragged. The workers who came to Mobile and Pascagoula to work in the shipyards there were from the backwoods of the South, "subnormal swamp and mountain folk" whom the locals described as "vermin"; elsewhere, they were called "squatters". They were accused of having loose morals, high illegitimacy rates, and of allowing [[prostitution]] to thrive in their "Hillbilly Havens". The trailers themselves &ndash; sometimes purchased second- or third-hand &ndash; were often unsightly, unsanitary and dilapidated, causing communities to zone them away from the more desirable areas, which meant away from schools, stores, another necessary facilities, often literally on the other side of the railroad tracks.<ref name=isen240 />
==In art, entertainment, and media== {{or section|date=May 2018}} {{list dispute|date=May 2018}} ===Music=== [[Billy Ray Cyrus]]' song "Burn Down the Trailer Park" and [[Toby Keith]]'s song "Trailerhood" and contain humorous lyrics about living in a trailer park.
[[Colt Ford]]'s song "No Trash in My Trailer" (2009) tells of a [[redneck]]-type male who throws his girlfriend out of his mobile home, the message being "there ain't no trash in my trailer, since the day I threw you outta here."
The song "Trailer Trash" appears on [[Modest Mouse]]'s album ''[[The Lonesome Crowded West]]'' (1997).
[[Eminem]] refers to himself as "Dale Earnhardt of the trailer park, the White Trash God" in his song "Rap God" from the album ''[[The Marshall Mathers LP 2]]'' (2013).
[[Lana Del Rey]]'s persona is portrayed as a "cheap trailer trash and everyone knows it" in the song "Boarding School". Trailer park references also appear on numerous other songs, including "Hundred Dollar Bill", "Yayo" and "Trash Magic".
===Television=== Most of the residents of the Pimmett Hills Trailer Park on ''[[My Name Is Earl]]'' fit this stereotype to some degree or another.
The [[Television in Canada|Canadian]] [[television]] series ''[[Trailer Park Boys]]'', done in [[mockumentary]] style, documents the misadventures of the residents of the Sunnyvale Trailer Park.
